---<br>
<br>
She stood above his body, her eyes set a blaze. How dare anyone call her a half-breed? They didn't know, or did they? Yet, how could they know of her past? Of her present? Did they know her mother, father, sister, brother, were dead? No, they didn't. They probably didn't even know them. Especially those of her own generation or younger. <br>
<br>
She took a pitcher of beer off a near by customer's table and splashed it into the eyes of her interogater. Grinning, as she saw him roll over trying to protect himself. Too bad he couldn't get up, and actually fight though. T'was too weak to begin with. One punch had him doubling over, and one push he was on the floor.<br>
<br>
She knew everyone in the bar was watching, but that didn't stop her. They'd learn not to ask the wrong questions, they'd know not to call her a half-breed. Though she was, that didn't matter. Then they'd learn not to mess with a Fier'Dal with the Tier'Dal power fueling them.<br>
<br>
She began to chant. A small boy ran to the arms of his mother, as they heard the crash of lightning outside. Her chanting grew louder, as did the storm just beyond the door. The barkeep, sounded the guards to come and remove her from his bar, but they couldn't see a thing do to the rains that were beginning to flood the streets. <br>
<br>
As the wind speeds began to pick up, her eyes began to glow. Arms extended to the Gods, she cried out as the power surge was just beginning. Crash after crash was heard outside. They were all scared. Men began to try and take her down, but with one glance at them they went flying against a near by wall. <br>
<br>
Her cloak came and gathered about her with none of her actions to help it. <br>
<br>
&quot;Mother, I love you. Father, I hate you. Ravyn and MJ forgive me!&quot;<br>
<br>
With that a bolt of lightning hit the small bar. No one, knew who did it, because there were no witnesses. If there were, they had all died in the fire. The Guards claimed it were just a sign from the Gods. Too bad, it was just the confusions of an adolescent's past...<br>
<br>
<br>
Storm - 2<br>
---<br>
<br>
A roaring fire blazed in a cauldron before a figure in robes of browns and greens, their head and face covered by a hood of shadows. Bared within their right hand a beaten, leather bound book, by their left a simple leaf.<br>
<br>
Opening the beaten book they began to chant. As their voice filled the large darkened room the fire began to die down. Once the room was no longer filled by the fire's light, their left hand lingered over the cauldron.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mother Tunare, bring them to me,&quot; and with those few words the figure released the leaf into the cauldron. Within brief seconds a blaze of green erupted from the iron cast pit, filling the room with an eerie green aura and consuming the floor with a thick, yellow mist.<br>
<br>
Stepping closer to the transformed flames, the figure removed their hood, revealing a woman in her mid-40's. The light from the fire cast green shadows hiding the color in her features. <br>
<br>
As she reached for the pouch about her neck she began to chant. Her chanting grew louder as she removed the contents of the pouch.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sister Luna, come help me find your daughter...&quot;<br>
<br>
The woman dropped a dried leaf into the flame.<br>
<br>
&quot;Replicon, my brother-in-law, come help me find your daughter...&quot;<br>
<br>
In the same fashion as before she dropped a piece of blackened alloy into the flame.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ravyn, my nephew, come help me find your sister...&quot;<br>
<br>
She continues by dropping a Raven's feather into the flame.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mariijay, my niece, come help me find your sister...&quot;<br>
<br>
She releases a red ribbon into the flame.<br>
<br>
&quot;Goddess Tunare, come help me find your child...&quot;<br>
<br>
She drops an Evergreen Leaf into the Cauldron.<br>
<br>
Closing her eyes, she chants. The energy about her causes her robes and hair to fly in all directions. The green aura shifts to a calm, soothing white as 4 ghostly figures appear in the mist.<br>
<br>
/Sister/... <br>
<br>
&quot;Luna?&quot;<br>
<br>
/Aye, 'tis I. My daughter has run off I see./<br>
<br>
The woman opened her eyes and looked her deceased family in the pits of mist that made their eyes. Sighing she continues, &quot;Yes, much like you had in your younger, living years...&quot;<br>
<br>
/I know. Do you wish to know where she is?/<br>
<br>
&quot;Indeed.&quot;<br>
<br>
The little girl to the left of the woman ghost spoke, /Where there are storms you will find her./<br>
<br>
Then the boy, /Where there are fires you will find her./<br>
<br>
Then the man, /Where protection is needed, you will find her./<br>
<br>
Finally the woman, /In your heart you will find her./<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't understand...&quot;<br>
<br>
The man hugged his wife, /She is confused, she needs to travel. Her past is hard to handle, but she feels she must protect her family from ridicule./<br>
<br>
The boy piped in, /Her punishment to those who accuse, laugh, point, stare, is death./<br>
<br>
/Well, not neccesarily. She loves to have fun, you can't take her love of life away from her./ Adds the young girl.<br>
<br>
&quot;You can find her in bars causing mischief and havok. You can find her worshipping Bristlebane. You can sense her love, but feel her hate.&quot; Came a voice behind the woman.<br>
<br>
Turning sharply, the woman falls to her knees, &quot;Mother Tunare.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;She is my child, as much as Lunaria's though she's been taken by Bristlebane. Her freedom has led her to mischief, and has led you to your lack of seeing her. Yet, she will come home... When she is ready for the answers, for the truth, and direct story of her past, of her future, of her path... She will come... or /they/ will lead her home. Though I've lost her to Bristlebane you have not lost her, never shall you. She'll come home...&quot;<br>
<br>
~~~<br>
<br>
Dyuio sat up sharply, sweat pouring from her pores. She looked about, no Cauldron, no spirits, no Tunare. /Still no Dahnyella.../ she thought.<br>
<br>
Sighing, she forced herself out of bed and walked to her wash table. Washing her face, she thought back to her dream. It felt so real. Wasn't it though? Looking up at the mirror right above the wash bowl, she saw it change. Swirling and twisting as lightning crashed outside, she began to see the words appear...<br>
<br>
She'll be home...<br>
<br>
<br>
Storm - 3<br>
---<br>
<br>
Dahnyella arose to the light pouring in frantically through her rented room's window. Groaning, she pulled her Bear Skin blanket over her head and tried desperately to will sleep back to her.<br>
<br>
Precious seconds later, the couple in the room beside her started fighting. She could hear the muffled voice of a man ranting, and a woman's cries. Things were starting to get thrown as the man's anger grew. Thudding, breaking, and shattering on the conjoint wall with Dahyella's very own room. /Isn't anybody going to stop them?/ <br>
<br>
She tried to cover her ears with the pillow the Inn had provided her, but it didn't work, because just then she heard the sound of a sword being unsheathed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Son of a bitch,&quot; Dahnyella threw her blanket off of herself, and stormed into the room beside her. She stood in the door way a second, waiting for just the right moment.<br>
<br>
&quot;Damn it, Woman! Listen to me for a change would yeh!? Maybe you'll listen to me if you were dead. Wouldn't ye... What in Rallos' name... &quot; The man began to feel a breeze upon his legs, his arms, his neck, his face. The 2 handed sword he held above his head began to waver as the breeze picked up. <br>
<br>
The man couldn't look around, because he was held in place by this unforseen wind. The woman on the other hand, brushed her hair away from her eyes, and glanced at the door. Before her stood a young woman, her eyes were glowing and focused on the sword, her fingers at her temples, and her mouth moving but no words coming out.<br>
<br>
As the winds picked up the woman pressed farther against the wall, still keeping an eye on the young lass at the door, and having her ears shut off to her husband's cursing.<br>
<br>
Suddenly a gust of wind erupted through the room, and swiped the sword right from the man's hands, sending it careening into the wall just inches next to the door way. <br>
<br>
&quot;What the...&quot; the man felt the wind begin to die, and he began to scan the room. Just as he was about to see Dahnyella, she unleashed a powerful round house kick to his jaw.<br>
<br>
The popping sound of his jaw disconnecting from his rather empty Barbaric skull, was pleasing and brought music to Dahnyella's ears. It was in perfect harmony with his screams of agony and pain.<br>
<br>
&quot;Quite the wimpy Warrior aren't we?&quot; Dahnyella asked sarcastically, summoning another gust of wind and slamming him into the wall. <br>
<br>
&quot;You bit...&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Dahyella chanted a few words, and held a hand to the floor, slowly vines began to encircle the man and held him tight to the floor. He was trying so hard to curse, but they came out as moans and groans of pain, anger, and resent towards her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Excuse me, but one who can not deal with such physical endeavours... Well, Hun, let me just say this. If I have you on your knees now. You have no right to be slapping around this woman, you swore on your life to protect. You're not really protecting her by throwing her about like a rag doll are ye?&quot; <br>
<br>
The man glowered, and Dahnyella stooped right next to him, sliding a hand around his throat, she whispered next to his ear, &quot;Pleasant dreams...&quot;<br>
<br>
With that she hit his pressure point sending him into a forgetful sleep. The woman gaped at her, &quot;Is he?&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella shook her head, &quot;Just asleep, but when he wakes up he'll think you did all the damage, and trust me. He won't mess with ya again.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank ye.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella nodded as she peered out the window the looked back to the woman assessing her tired, features, &quot;Looks like you've had a rough morning.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella slid an arm around the woman's shoulders, &quot;Let me get ye a drink in town. You can vent to me what's been happening. Hell he won't be up for a while.&quot;<br>
<br>
The woman grinned, &quot;Let's go.&quot;<br>
<br>
- - - <br>
<br>
Dyuio listened to her daughter, Harmonee, playing her Lute and singing in the living room as she prepared breakfast in the kitchen. Humming along to some of her daughter's original pieces she cut up fruits, and fried some eggs. <br>
<br>
She couldn't stop thinking about the constant dreams she was having. They were all about her niece, whom she missed dreadfully. While in her sleep it was as if she could feel every emotion Dahnyella had felt herself through out the day.<br>
<br>
She could remember one from just a few days ago. Dahnyella sat at a bar with a bunch of, she guessed friends, as she held a mug high and sang Ancient Drinking songs with them. She could feel her happiness, but she could also feel the pain that welled with inside her. Dyuio knew Dahnyella knew nothing about her past before age 4. She knew nothing of her mother, she knew little of her father. For all she knew was he was Dark, an Inkie. People knew this. Dahnyella didn't, and for some reason they just taunted her for it, like she knew it all already. She didn't though. It was something she needed to learn. She needed to come home.<br>
<br>
Dyuio sighed, closing her eyes she remebered what Tunare had said to her in her sleep. /If she doesn't on her own, they will lead her home.../<br>
<br>
Who was /they/? Who was possibly going to help her home? Who would know?<br>
<br>
Then she looked at the window, then at her daughter in the living room, &quot;She'll be home...&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
Storm - 4<br>
---<br>
<br>
&quot;Can I get you anything, Lady?&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella looked up with a seductive smile on her face, &quot;I'll take a glass of Elven Wine.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Sure thing,&quot; the Bartender smiled back, and readied her drink.<br>
<br>
As Dahnyella sat at the bar, she scanned the room. /Nice crowd.../ she thought. To her left was a Dwarf in old rustic, bronze armor, at the table in the back was a group of men and women discussing something highly important. Travellers? Guild members? Party members stopping for just a wee break? She began to cast her senses...<br>
<br>
&quot;Here you go, m'lady,&quot; Dahnyella looked up at the Bartender setting down the drink before her, &quot;That will be 3 silver.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella nodded and reached for her coin pouch, slightly annoyed her concentration got disrupted. Yet, what right did she have ease-dropping? <br>
<br>
Just as she had the money counted a young man came by and dropped the tab into the Bartender's hand, &quot;On me.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Bartender nodded, and went off to help his other customers. Dahnyella smiled warmly at the fellow, &quot;Thanks,&quot; she said as she took a sip from her glass.<br>
<br>
&quot;Anything for a lady,&quot; he said with a devilish grin on his face. She had to blush. Charming, she had to admit. He stood about 6 foot, sandy colored hair, and the deepest blue eyes you could imagine. Dahnyella could only sit and look at him in awe. Complete and utter awe, he was gorgeous to say the least.<br>
<br>
Dahnyella sat and just looked at him, and to her benefit he looked right back at least until...<br>
<br>
&quot;Hail, Talcos!&quot;<br>
<br>
Yeah, that. <br>
<br>
The man spun around to face his greeter, a smile spread across his face, &quot;Mercilles, friend, how are ye?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Quite fine. Speaking of fine, quite a glimmer in your eye at the moment,&quot; he glanced at Dahnyella, &quot;I can see why,&quot; he took Dahnyella's hand and kissed it, &quot;Mercilles.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dahnyella,&quot; she smiled. Mercilles stood about 6'7&quot;, much taller than his friend, his skin was the color of chocolate, his hair and eyes even a deeper shade. <br>
<br>
&quot;Beautiful.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella blushed, &quot;Thanks.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mercilles grinned, then took the seat to her left. The one that remained open between her and the Dwarf. Then she grinned herself. This was going to be one long, fun, and interesting night.<br>
<br>
- - - <br>
<br>
Around 11PM the bar was packed. Most of the men surrounded her as she drank and told jokes, getting uproars out of every one of them. Then something nipped her senses. Something she couldn't put a finger on. She secretly cast her senses. To her acknowledgement the disturbance was only feet away. A young Dark Elf about her own age stalked into the bar. She had a cloak of deep black, that made her eyes scream. They were the brightest blue. Considering her skin tone, they stook out even more.<br>
<br>
&quot;Out of my way fool!&quot; She hissed as she shoved the dwarf that sat to the left of her off his stool.<br>
<br>
The Bartender looked at her, &quot;A glass of Elven Blood Wine,&quot; she said with out even acknowledging him.<br>
<br>
Dahnyella swiveled on her stool to look at her, she told Mercilles to move a bit then she connected... /Elven Blood Wine? How could you like that!/<br>
<br>
Then Dark Elf shot her a look, /If you have something to say to me say it out loud you fair skinned hooker,/ she shot back. <br>
<br>
Dahnyella glanced about her, and her anger rose a bit. /Why should I?/<br>
<br>
She grinned, /I have my reasons./<br>
<br>
Dahnyella emitted a low growl, &quot;Elven Blood Wine? That's sick! Why drink Elf Blood?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;If it's Wood Elven blood, why not?&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella grabbed her staff, and pictured herself drawing runes of comfort upon her forehead. /Calm down.../<br>
<br>
&quot;Why don't you just sit there and drink your nasty wine, and leave me be. I don't want anything to do with you.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Dark Elf just drank her wine, as if Dahnyella wasn't even there. She decided to do the same. Turning back to talk with Talcos, she noticed he was turned and swiped a few platinum out of his pocket. Slipping the platinum into her coin pouch, she felt someone's eyes on her. Closing her eyes she knew exactally who it was, /Do you mind?/<br>
<br>
Dahnyella recieved no reply. In frustration she took a huge swig of her drink, and began drumming her fingers on her spell book.<br>
<br>
The Bartender set another drink in front of Dahnyella, how many was that now? No more likely how many BOTTLES had she gone through. She turned to Talcos starting on her new drink, and smiled. He flashed her a grin, and put an arm around her. <br>
<br>
As Talcos began telling jokes and stories, Dahnyella couldn't help but laugh. They weren't even funny, it was her first sign of verging to drunken stupor. <br>
<br>
As the drinks came, she drank 'em. She didn't want to just waste 'em. The tab was beginning to add up. <br>
<br>
Dahnyella kept laughing, but she was picking up on something, alarm? Maybe? She glanced over her shoulder to look at the Dark Elf secretly, as if she her just flipping her hair. It was from her alright, but why?<br>
<br>
Dahnyella carried on, then in mid-sip it happened. The Dark Elf had walked over removing Talcos' arms from her, and stood between them. She looked directly at him, &quot;Leave. There is nothing here for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Talcos glanced over her, slightly confused, then he shot a look at Dahnyella. She was even confused, &quot;Hey! What do you think you're doing. You can't tell him what to do!&quot;<br>
<br>
She spun on Dahnyella fast as lightning, &quot;Listen, he is trying to take advantage of you, trying to get you drunk so he can have his way, steal your things, and then leave you on the floor of this bar the next day.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella couldn't believe it, he and her were just having a good time. He was being buying her a few, &quot;No he's not...&quot; Dahnyella could no longer feel his presence, she could but not strong, &quot;Is he?&quot; She glanced over the Dark Elf's shoulder, and he was heading for the door, &quot;I guess you were right.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I always am.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella looked at her, &quot;What's your name?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Bellona.&quot;<br>
<br>
She had to giggle, &quot;Bellie.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bellona grumbled, &quot;And your's?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Dahnyella.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bellona just nodded, Dahnyella watched as she ordered a coffee and handed it to her, &quot;Drink.&quot;<br>
<br>
She gave an apprehensive glance, then drank away. &quot;Thank you, I guess.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Just keep drinking, then I'll take you home and you can rest some, you look as if you have not slept in days.&quot; <br>
<br>
She was right too. She hadn't. Either the sleep that is willed to her is disrupted, or she is too scared to actually sleep. Dahnyella just nodded, &quot;I definately feel that way.&quot;<br>
<br>
Dahnyella finally finished up the coffee, gathered up her spellbook and staff, and then they set off for the wee inn Bellona was currently residing in.<br>
<br>
The room was your normal. Bed, table and chairs, dresser, wash table. Much like the one's Dahnyella has spent her last couple years in. Apart from her Aunt Dyuio's home in Kelethin. <br>
<br>
